  faq={[
    {
      q: 'When do I need a crown instead of a filling?',
      a: 'A crown is typically recommended when a tooth has extensive decay, a large existing filling that has failed, a crack that extends into the tooth structure, or after root canal therapy. If less than half the tooth structure is intact, a filling alone won\'t provide adequate support.',
    },
    {
      q: 'How long does getting a crown take?',
      a: 'Most crown treatment requires two appointments. At the first visit, we prepare the tooth, take digital impressions, and place a temporary crown. The permanent crown is fabricated in a dental lab and cemented at your second visit, typically 2–3 weeks later.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Will my crown look natural?',
